# Phase 5.1 Session 5b — nested broadcast with MvNormal inner body.
#
# Per spec §04: kernel-broadcast over a user kernel whose body is
# itself a `broadcast(MvNormal, …)`. The Phase 4.4 nested-broadcast
# detector already recognises the two-axis pattern; Session 5b
# extends it to accept VECTOR_OUTPUT_DISTRIBUTIONS (MvNormal) as the
# inner head — closing the §22.2(d) story for the INNER case.
#
# Model shape:
#   - K_outer = 3 (groups, each with its own scale_outer).
#   - K_inner = 4 (per-group "subject" observations, each with its
#     own per-cell n-vector mu_inner).
#   - Inner body draws MvNormal(mu_inner, cov_shared) where mu_inner
#     varies per inner cell.
#
# Output shape: [N, K_outer, K_inner * n] atom-major, where n=2
# (MvNormal event dim). Per (outer, inner, dim) the value is a
# Normal(mu_inner[dim], cov_shared[dim, dim]).
#
# Test oracles (in nested-broadcast-mvnormal-inner.test.ts):
#   - Shape: y.value.shape == [N, K_outer, K_inner * n].
#   - Finite output values.
#   - Per (outer, inner) sample mean ≈ mu_inner_per_cell.

mu_inner_per_cell = rowstack([
  [0.0, 0.0], [1.0, -1.0], [-2.0, 3.0], [0.5, 0.5]
])
cov_shared = rowstack([[1.0, 0.3], [0.3, 0.5]])

# Outer kernel takes a scale-out param but doesn't actually use it
# in the inner body (Session 5b MVP doesn't yet thread outer per-
# atom refs into MvNormal params; that lands in Session 5c+).
# The outer broadcast iterates K_outer=3 times.

inner_kernel = kernelof(
  broadcast(MvNormal, mu = mu_inner_per_cell, cov = cov_shared),
  scale_outer = scale_outer
)

scales = [1.0, 1.0, 1.0]
y = broadcast(inner_kernel, scale_outer = scales)
